					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So you could arbitrarly decide that any value is a NULL pointer. I'd say that other than $0000, $ffff would be a great candidate too, as it's unlikely you'd want to point there, and it's as easy to test (just AND two bytes and compare with $ff).</div><br />Only if you're actually writing the compiler. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> I'm fairly sure cc65 will assume that the null pointer's underlying representation is a bit pattern of all zeroes, and will generate pointer comparison code based on that. There's no way to override this behavior without modifying the compiler.<br /><br />For anyone interested, here's a good rundown of null pointers in C: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://c-faq.com/null/">http://c-faq.com/null/</a><!-- m --></div>

					
